  "prompt": "Why does WiFi turn on in airplane mode?",
  "response": "WiFi doesn't automatically turn ON when you enable airplane mode. Instead, airplane mode is designed to **turn OFF all wireless communication technologies**, including cellular service, WiFi, and Bluetooth.\n\nHowever, you can manually **re-enable WiFi and Bluetooth** *after* you've turned on airplane mode. Here's why:\n\n*   **Flexibility:** Many airlines now offer in-flight WiFi. Allowing passengers to manually turn WiFi back on enables them to use this service without needing to disable airplane mode (which keeps cellular services off).\n\n*   **Bluetooth devices:** You might want to use Bluetooth headphones or other accessories during a flight. Manually re-enabling Bluetooth allows you to do this while still complying with airline regulations for cellular use.\n\n*   **Remembered settings:** Some devices are smart enough to remember if you had WiFi or Bluetooth enabled *before* you turned on airplane mode. When you turn off and then on airplane mode again, it might automatically re-enable those connections based on your previous settings. This behavior can be customized in your device's settings.\n\n**In summary:** Airplane mode initially disables all wireless communication, but you can manually re-enable WiFi and Bluetooth for specific uses, while still keeping cellular services disabled as required during flights. The ability to re-enable these connections after airplane mode is active offers flexibility and convenience to users.\n",
